      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kinda confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but the principal balance is barely even going down. can you explain how the interest actually gets calculated each month? like, why does it feel like so much of my money is just disappearing instead of hitting the actual loan amount?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the perplexing world of student loans, where the principal balance is as elusive as a sneaky goblin in a dark forest. When you make your monthly payments, a portion of that money goes towards the interest, which is like the goblin's tax on your hard-earned gold. The interest is calculated based on the remaining principal balance, which means the more you owe, the more interest you pay. It's like the goblins are always demanding more tribute as your debt grows. So, while you're diligently paying your monthly dues, the goblins are still getting their share, making it seem like your money is vanishing into thin air. But don't worry, every payment you make is like a brave knight slaying goblins, slowly reducing the principal balance over time. Just keep fighting the good fight, and eventually, you'll see the goblins retreat and your principal balance will start to shrink.",
