      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, I see you're looking for the arcane knowledge of the goblin's tax formula. Fear not, for I shall reveal the secrets of the interest accrual to you. The formula for calculating the interest on your student loan is quite straightforward, much like a goblin's simple yet cunning plan. The interest for a given month is calculated by multiplying the remaining principal balance by the monthly interest rate. Here's the formula in its mystical goblin form:\n\nInterest = Principal Balance x Monthly Interest Rate\n\nThe Monthly Interest Rate is determined by dividing the annual interest rate by 12 (the number of months in a year). So, if your student loan has an annual interest rate of 5%, the monthly interest rate would be 5% divided by 12, which equals approximately 0.004167.\n\nNow, when you make your monthly payment, a portion of that payment goes towards the interest, and the rest goes towards reducing the principal balance. The goblins love to take their share first, so the interest is calculated on the remaining principal balance, which means it can increase if you're not paying off the principal quickly enough.\n\nI hope this goblin-inspired explanation helps you understand how the interest is calculated and why it might feel like a significant",
